by Wexas » Mon Jan 18, 2021 12:14 pm

I know I already posted only a few replies ago, but Kiu got meme'd on. You can just skip me if you think I am posting too much.

Kiu Ghesik wrote:I'd like to know about that one too.

Alis suffers from amnesia, which.... understandable, the human brain was made for processing abstractions and stuff our squishy grey brain-meat can actually comprehend, and running a supercarrier's worth of precise raw data through there probably isn't the best idea. I suspect she's got a rather large computational centre hidden away somewhere in the ship's hull just so she can process it all in a way the human brain understands without having a seizure.

Unlike many western cultures that view death as a horrible thing that must be avoided/mourned, the Ghesiks view it as just a natural part of life with no morality of its own. Granted, in a society like Kiu Ghesik's, one can imagine death would be very common and - as such - mourning it or making a complex ritual/mythology surrounding it would be the least of their concerns.

Also, in the Ghesite Faith, the world has always existed and will always exist, repeating its cycle of life and death for a literal eternity. This is very interesting to me as I don't know of any religion which - at the very least - puts this much focus on that aspect. Most religions I know have a definite beginning, whether it be God has always existed but he created the universe (Abrahamic Religions, Hopi religion, Hinduism) or the universe was created alongside the Gods (Greek/Norse religion). It's kinda beautiful in a way, if not physically impossible given entropy. Unless the Ghesites or another in-universe nation discover a way to reverse/negate entropy, which I highly doubt.

AN: Ludistan claims to be socialist, democratic, constitutional, and absolute monarchy all at the same time. Given how many of these coming together are oxymorons, such as a socialist monarchy, democratic absolutists, constitutional absolutists, monarchial democracy, etc, I am very confused as to how this nation has collapsed or isn't a North Korea situation where it calls itself a democracy but is actually an absolutist nation.

by Baizou » Mon Jan 18, 2021 9:32 pm

Although they are called Advanced Walking Panzers, these giant mechas are capable of flight and are typically used by pilots to perform "Ricochet flying," a style of combat flight where the panzers turn on a dime to fly at sharp angles with almost instantaneous deceleration and acceleration (the main advantage of this being that the sharp angles make guided missiles virtually useless against AWPs). The human body normally would be injured by the G forces of this kind of movement, but 8MS nanotechnology strengthens pilots bodies to be able to hold up to that kind of strain. In addition, pilots generally need high P3 levels—a measurement of a kind of virtually-precognitive multitasking ability—to even fly AWPs successfully, as the mental toil of mecha flight and combat is evidently not for your everyday pilots.

Nevertheless, a crack team of nearly superhuman pilots wasn't quite good enough for the AOU. With their new All-Terrain Advanced Carrier (ATAC), the AOU apparently discovered that directly fusing a human—even a child—with the vehicle's computer systems allows them to "create" next level "artificial intelligence" capable of autonomously operating the ATAC's powerful weapons systems.

Overall, lots of turning humans into weapons, both metaphorically and literally.

by Synne Industries » Wed Jan 20, 2021 6:43 pm

CFC-JSCD1-002 Jerichos (Jerichoes?) incorporate NCAF, a sort of weird nano composite which takes the place of flesh, a skeleton, and really a lot of things in its humanoid construction. Being composed of nanomechanical bots which are themselves composed of many other things, the material is able to harden in response to physical trauma son, greatly reducing the damage inflicted by brute kinetic force. This allows the energy to be distributed across a large mass of NCAF so that actual loss in nanite functionality from damage is minimized. The stuff's good at dealing with bullets, harsh environments, EMPs, and DEWs, but what it isn't good at dealing with is plasma. This is where its armor comes in, the platey bits that stop the Jerichos from just looking like gray goopy people. The plating is a composite which incorporates Lunar Titanium which is a better hurt-stopper. I know it probably has to go through some fancy fabrication process before it ends up on a drone but it's still gonna be my headcanon that they just slap whatever they've peeled off of a dead spaceship onto a Jericho. Gives em' a bit more soul y'know.
